14.04 and then builds the rest of the coupling infrastructure around this (using gcc from conda and mpich build within conda).\nThis has a known problem on Ubuntu 16.04 as the version of libc < 2.5 so building from source may be essential.\n\n\n\n=Container version in Singularity=\n\nAn MPI aware container that is designed to work on supercomputers. This is currently under testing.\n\n=Building from Source on linux=\n\nTypically OpenFOAM is the most tricky bit of the installation process, in part because it takes so long to build.\nIt is recommend that it be built from the github source,\n\nhttps://github.com/OpenFOAM/OpenFOAM-3.0.x.git OpenFOAM-3.0.x\n\nas a number of fixes are included which plagued the previous packaged version.\nSetting up OpenFOAM then proceeds following the normal installation process [https://openfoam.org/download/3-0-1-source/]. \n\n\nThis assumes that the version of OpenFOAM has been cloned from git (or downloaded) along with the CPL APP as follows: \n\n     git clone https://github.com/Crompulence/CPL_APP_OPENFOAM-3.0.1.git CPL_APP_OPENFOAM-3.0.1\n\n\n1) Go to the OpenFOAM folder.\n\n2) cd to CPL_APP_OPENFOAM-3.0.1/config [https://github.com/Crompulence/CPL_APP_OPENFOAM-3.0.1] and copy \"prefs.sh\" to the etc directory in OpenFOAM using \"cp CPL_APP_OPENFOAM-3.0.1/config/prefs.sh OpenFOAM-3.0.1/etc\". Note this requires the correct MPI_ROOT variable obtained from the base directory of your MPI installation using mpicc -show (WARNING: assumes mpich and not tried with openmpi). \n\n3) Go back to the socket\'s root directory and `source SOURCEME.sh` from this directory.\n\n4) Go to the ThirdParty folder and ./Allwmake. If you have the dependencies satisfied, it should compile. Now \"cd ..\".\n\n5) Apply cpl-socket/config/ptscotchDecomp.patch by doing \"make patch-scotch\" in the root directory. This fix a redefinition of MPI_Init while compiling OpenFOAM. This error happens at least for mpich3.2. I have not tried with earlier versions.\n\n6) 