== Links ==\n* [http://www.cpl-library.org/ Back to CPL library main page]\n* [https://zenodo.org/record/56208#.WJrZN56YNhg The DOI for CPL library]\n* [https://github.com/Crompulence/cpl-library Github site for CPL library]\n* [https://github.com/Crompulence/cpl-library/wiki/CPL-Library Github wiki page]\n* [http://edwardsmith.co.uk Personal web page for Edward Smith with more information on wider use and scope]','utf-8'),(83,'Welcome to the CPL library wiki. \nThis contains documentation, discussion and accounts of setting up coupled cases.\n\n== CPL library ==\n - Running [[CPL library in Docker]] and using CPL library to run a case between [[Two Separate Docker Containers]]\n - How best to [[run CPL library]]\n - A discussion of the [[coupler philosophy]]\n - Input [[COUPLER.in file]] and supported commands\n - An example of a [[MOCK CPL]] script to be used for coupled development\n - An overview of [[ndArray]], [[CPL force]] and [[CPL field]] helper classes which are used to apply constraints on particle codes in coupled simulation.\n - A tutorial on setting up your own CPL force and field objects\n - How to setup a [[custom install of mpi4py]] on a supercomputer for use with the python wrapper of CPL library.\n\n== OpenFOAM ==\n - A guide outlining the [[setup of OpenFOAM]] for use in coupled simulation.\n - An overview of the various top level [[OpenFOAM solvers]].\n\n== LAMMPS ==\n - An overview of [[deployment of LAMMPS]] with coupling.\n - A discussion of the [[LAMMPS CPL interface]], the available [[LAMMPS input syntax]] to use fix_cpl_init and the LAMMPS CPL APP [[fix_cpl_force]].\n - A [[Minimal tutorial on creating new Drag Forces]]\n - An [[Extended Tutorial on creating new Drag Forces]]\n\n== Links ==\n* [http://www.cpl-library.org/ Back to CPL library main page]\n* [https://zenodo.org/record/56208#.WJrZN56YNhg The DOI for CPL library]\n* [https://github.com/Crompulence/cpl-library Github site for CPL library]\n* [https://github.com/Crompulence/cpl-library/wiki/CPL-Library Github wiki page]\n* [http://edwardsmith.co.uk Personal web page for Edward Smith with more information on wider use and scope]','utf-8'),(84,'\nFirst you need to get Docker, see [here](https://docs.docker.com/). \n\nFor Ubuntu 16.04, this proceeds as follows:\n\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\n sudo apt-get update\n sudo apt-get install \\\n     apt-transport-https \\\n     ca-certificates \\\n     curl \\\n     software-properties-common\ncurl -fsSL https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu/gpg | sudo apt-key add -\nsudo apt-key fingerprint 0EBFCD88\nsudo add-apt-repository \\\n   \"deb [arch=amd64] https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu \\\n   $(lsb_release -cs) \\\n   stable\"\nsudo apt-get update\nsudo apt-get install docker-ce\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nThen we get the CPL library docker image:\n\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\nsudo docker pull cpllibrary/cpl-library\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nNext, we want to start this case\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\nsudo docker run -it --name cplrun cpllibrary/cpl-library\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nThe range of different tests can be run, for example\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\ntest-pytest-mapping \ntest-pytest-initialisation \ntest-examples \ntest-gtests\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nIn order to understand a minimal coupled examples, check out\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\ncd /cpl-library/examples/minimal_send_recv_mocks\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nHave a look at the file, they give an example of a minimal coupled case,\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"python\">\n#!/usr/bin/env python\nfrom mpi4py import MPI\nfrom cplpy import CPL\n\ncomm = MPI.COMM_WORLD\nCPL = CPL()\nCFD_COMM = CPL.init(CPL.CFD_REALM)\nCPL.setup_cfd(CFD_COMM.Create_cart([1, 1, 1]), xyzL=[1.0, 1.0, 1.0], \n              xyz_orig=[0.0, 0.0, 0.0], ncxyz=[32, 32, 32])\nrecv_array, send_array = CPL.get_arrays(recv_size=4, send_size=1)\n\nfor time in range(5):\n\n    recv_array, ierr = CPL.recv(recv_array)\n    print(\"CFD\", time, recv_array[0,0,0,0])\n    send_array[0,:,:,:] = 2.*time\n    CPL.send(send_array)\n\nCPL.finalize()\nMPI.Finalize()\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nThis initialises CPL library, creates a topology with 32 cells in each direction with one processes\nand loops five times sending and receiving data each time.\n\nThe MD file is very similar, but instead has 8 processes.\nThis coupled example can be run as follows:\n\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\ncplexec -c 1 minimal_CFD.py -m 8 minimal_MD.py\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nwhich creates two MPI runs, writes a PORT file and merges the two MPI_COMM_WORLD s\n\nOr, this can be run in the MPMD mode, using,\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\nmpiexec -n 1 python minimal_CFD.py -n 8 python minimal_MD.py\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nwhich runs both codes in a single MPI_COMM_WORLD instance.\nBe aware that this becomes important if either coupled code uses MPI_COMM_WORLD\nin any of its MPI communications (which almost every code does).','utf-8'),(85,'\nFirst you need to get Docker, see [here](https://docs.docker.com/). \n\nFor Ubuntu 16.04, this proceeds as follows:\n\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\n sudo apt-get update\n sudo apt-get install \\\n     apt-transport-https \\\n     ca-certificates \\\n     curl \\\n     software-properties-common\ncurl -fsSL https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu/gpg | sudo apt-key add -\nsudo apt-key fingerprint 0EBFCD88\nsudo add-apt-repository \\\n   \"deb [arch=amd64] https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu \\\n   $(lsb_release -cs) \\\n   stable\"\nsudo apt-get update\nsudo apt-get install docker-ce\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nThen we get the CPL library docker image:\n\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\nsudo docker pull cpllibrary/cpl-library\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nNext, we want to start this case\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\nsudo docker run -it --name cplrun cpllibrary/cpl-library\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nThe range of different tests can be run, for example\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\ntest-pytest-mapping \ntest-pytest-initialisation \ntest-examples \ntest-gtests\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nIn order to understand a minimal coupled examples, check out\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\ncd /cpl-library/examples/minimal_send_recv_mocks\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nHave a look at the file, they give an example of a minimal coupled case,\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"python\">\n#!/usr/bin/env python\nfrom mpi4py import MPI\nfrom cplpy import CPL\n\ncomm = MPI.COMM_WORLD\nCPL = CPL()\nCFD_COMM = CPL.init(CPL.CFD_REALM)\nCPL.setup_cfd(CFD_COMM.Create_cart([1, 1, 1]), xyzL=[1.0, 1.0, 1.0], \n              xyz_orig=[0.0, 0.0, 0.0], ncxyz=[32, 32, 32])\nrecv_array, send_array = CPL.get_arrays(recv_size=4, send_size=1)\n\nfor time in range(5):\n\n    recv_array, ierr = CPL.recv(recv_array)\n    print(\"CFD\", time, recv_array[0,0,0,0])\n    send_array[0,:,:,:] = 2.*time\n    CPL.send(send_array)\n\nCPL.finalize()\nMPI.Finalize()\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nThis initialises CPL library, creates a topology with 32 cells in each direction with one processes\nand loops five times sending and receiving data each time.\n\nThe MD file is very similar, but instead has 8 processes.\nThis coupled example can be run as follows:\n\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\ncplexec -c 1 minimal_CFD.py -m 8 minimal_MD.py\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nwhich creates two MPI runs, writes a PORT file and merges the two MPI_COMM_WORLD s\n\nOr, this can be run in the MPMD mode, using,\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\nmpiexec -n 1 python minimal_CFD.py -n 8 python minimal_MD.py\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nwhich runs both codes in a single MPI_COMM_WORLD instance.\nBe aware that this becomes important if either coupled code uses MPI_COMM_WORLD\nin any of its MPI communications (which almost every code does).\n\n\nIf you want to run a coupled case and keep the output, you need to use docker volumes, which can be done as follows:\n\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\nsudo docker run -it --name cplrun --mount source=cpl-vol,target=/cplruns cpllibrary/cpl-library\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\n\nThe example codes should then be copied to /cplruns and run in this as above\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\nrsync -avP /cpl-library/examples/minimal_send_recv_mocks/ /runs/\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nThe output from the run will then be saved between runs \n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\ncd /runs/\ncplexec -c 1 minimal_CFD.py -m 8 minimal_MD.py\n</syntaxhighlight>\nThe only output in this run will be save in the /runs/cpl folder in the form of various header files.\n\nOn the host operating system this can be access using the command,\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\nsudo docker volume inspect cpl-vol\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nand getting the path, which in ubuntu defaults to \n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\n/var/lib/docker/volumes/cpl-vol/_data\nsyntaxhighlight','utf-8'),(86,'Before this case, take a look at the [[CPL library in Docker]] to see an introduction to running the MPI processes inside a single Docker container.\n\nHowever, a far more interesting application is to create two containers and then link the processes running in them with MPI sending information between them.\n\nFirst we need to get the CPL library docker image:\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\nsudo docker pull cpllibrary/cpl-library\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nNext, we want to start a coupled case with a persistent shared volume\nThe shared volume:\n  1) Will contain all the output of the run \n  2) Can allow coupling between two docker containers\nTo starts an interactive bash session called cplrun with volume cpl-vol mounted under folder runs\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\nsudo docker run -it --name cplrun1 --mount source=cpl-vol,target=/cplruns cpllibrary/cpl-library\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nIn the first docker container, copy an example to runs\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\nrsync -avP /cpl-library/examples/minimal_send_recv_mocks/ /runs/\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nChange directory to runs and run the CFD example\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\ncd /runs/\nmpiexec -n 1 python ./minimal_CFD.py\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nThis will create a PORT file in /runs/ which will be used to link to\nanother executable running in a second container.\nTo do this, we create in A NEW TERMINAL nd create a second docker \nimage sharing the same file system\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\nsudo docker run -it --name cplrun2 --mount source=cpl-vol,target=/cplruns cpllibrary/cpl-library\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nAgain, in this directory, we change to runs and create the corresponding MD run\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\ncd /runs/\nmpiexec -n 8 python ./minimal_MD.py\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nThe output from the coupled codes should appear in both terminals as they exchange information.\nThis has only been tested on a single machine, ssh keys and a shared file system \nwould need to be established between computers.\n\nTo see the location of the volume on the host system\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\nsudo docker volume inspect cpl-vol\n</syntaxhighlight>','utf-8'),(87,'Before this case, take a look at the [[CPL library in Docker]] to see an introduction to running the MPI processes inside a single Docker container.\n\nHowever, a far more interesting application is to create two containers and then link the processes running in them with MPI sending information between them.\n\nFirst we need to get the CPL library docker image:\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\nsudo docker pull cpllibrary/cpl-library\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nNext, we want to start a coupled case with a persistent shared volume\nThe shared volume:\n# Will contain all the output of the run \n# Can allow coupling between two docker containers\nTo starts an interactive bash session called cplrun with volume cpl-vol mounted under folder runs\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\nsudo docker run -it --name cplrun1 --mount source=cpl-vol,target=/cplruns cpllibrary/cpl-library\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nIn the first docker container, copy an example to runs\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\nrsync -avP /cpl-library/examples/minimal_send_recv_mocks/ /runs/\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nChange directory to runs and run the CFD example\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\ncd /runs/\nmpiexec -n 1 python ./minimal_CFD.py\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nThis will create a PORT file in /runs/ which will be used to link to\nanother executable running in a second container.\nTo do this, we create in A NEW TERMINAL nd create a second docker \nimage sharing the same file system\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\nsudo docker run -it --name cplrun2 --mount source=cpl-vol,target=/cplruns cpllibrary/cpl-library\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nAgain, in this directory, we change to runs and create the corresponding MD run\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\ncd /runs/\nmpiexec -n 8 python ./minimal_MD.py\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nThe output from the coupled codes should appear in both terminals as they exchange information.\nThis has only been tested on a single machine, ssh keys and a shared file system \nwould need to be established between computers.\n\nTo see the location of the volume on the host system\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\nsudo docker volume inspect cpl-vol\n</syntaxhighlight>','utf-8'),(88,'\n=Install Docker=\n\nFirst you need to get Docker, see [here](https://docs.docker.com/). \n\nFor Ubuntu 16.04, this proceeds as follows:\n\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\n sudo apt-get update\n sudo apt-get install \\\n     apt-transport-https \\\n     ca-certificates \\\n     curl \\\n     software-properties-common\ncurl -fsSL https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu/gpg | sudo apt-key add -\nsudo apt-key fingerprint 0EBFCD88\nsudo add-apt-repository \\\n   \"deb [arch=amd64] https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu \\\n   $(lsb_release -cs) \\\n   stable\"\nsudo apt-get update\nsudo apt-get install docker-ce\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\n=Getting CPL library Docker Image=\n\nThen we get the CPL library docker image:\n\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\nsudo docker pull cpllibrary/cpl-library\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\n=Running CPL library with Docker=\n\n==Starting and Tests==\n\nNext, we want to start this case\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\nsudo docker run -it --name cplrun cpllibrary/cpl-library\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nThe cases which are available are found under examples,\nthese are detailed on the cpl library [website](http://www.cpl-library.org/user-guide/quick-start.shtml#linking)\nand include a [linking](http://www.cpl-library.org/user-guide/quick-start.shtml#linking) \nexample in Fortran, C++ and Python, as well as the \n[minimal code to couple](http://www.cpl-library.org/user-guide/quick-start.shtml#mock) in Python\nan [example](http://www.cpl-library.org/user-guide/quick-start.shtml#analysing) of visualising a coupled simulation\na case where an [interactive slider interface](http://www.cpl-library.org/user-guide/quick-start.shtml#interactive)\nis attached to a Fortran code and finally a fully functional [2D CFD and MD example](http://www.cpl-library.org/user-guide/quick-start.shtml#MD_CFD) in Python.\n\nThe range of different tests can be run, for example\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\ntest-pytest-mapping \ntest-pytest-initialisation \ntest-examples \ntest-gtests\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\n\n==A First Examples==\n\nIn order to understand a minimal coupled examples, check out\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\ncd /cpl-library/examples/minimal_send_recv_mocks\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nHave a look at the file, they give an example of a minimal coupled case,\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"python\">\n#!/usr/bin/env python\nfrom mpi4py import MPI\nfrom cplpy import CPL\n\ncomm = MPI.COMM_WORLD\nCPL = CPL()\nCFD_COMM = CPL.init(CPL.CFD_REALM)\nCPL.setup_cfd(CFD_COMM.Create_cart([1, 1, 1]), xyzL=[1.0, 1.0, 1.0], \n              xyz_orig=[0.0, 0.0, 0.0], ncxyz=[32, 32, 32])\nrecv_array, send_array = CPL.get_arrays(recv_size=4, send_size=1)\n\nfor time in range(5):\n\n    recv_array, ierr = CPL.recv(recv_array)\n    print(\"CFD\", time, recv_array[0,0,0,0])\n    send_array[0,:,:,:] = 2.*time\n    CPL.send(send_array)\n\nCPL.finalize()\nMPI.Finalize()\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nThis initialises CPL library, creates a topology with 32 cells in each direction with one processes\nand loops five times sending and receiving data each time.\n\nThe MD file is very similar, but instead has 8 processes.\nThis coupled example can be run as follows:\n\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\ncplexec -c 1 minimal_CFD.py -m 8 minimal_MD.py\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nwhich creates two MPI runs, writes a PORT file and merges the two MPI_COMM_WORLD s\n\nOr, this can be run in the MPMD mode, using,\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\nmpiexec -n 1 python minimal_CFD.py -n 8 python minimal_MD.py\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nwhich runs both codes in a single MPI_COMM_WORLD instance.\nBe aware that this becomes important if either coupled code uses MPI_COMM_WORLD\nin any of its MPI communications (which almost every code does).\n\n=Graphical User Interface=\n\nSome of the examples matplotlib and interactive GUI. In addition, there are grid design tools\nwhich can be used to setup a coupled run.\n\nGetting Docker to work with the host display can be a little tricky.\nThe following solution from [stackoverflow](https://stackoverflow.com/a/25280523) has been the most successful\n\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\nXSOCK=/tmp/.X11-unix\nXAUTH=/tmp/.docker.xauth\nxauth nlist :0 | sed -e \'s/^..../ffff/\' | xauth -f $XAUTH nmerge -\nsudo docker run -ti -e DISPLAY=\":0\" -v $XSOCK:$XSOCK -v $XAUTH:$XAUTH -e XAUTHORITY=$XAUTH cpllibrary/cpl-library\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\n=Mounting Docker Volumes=\n\n\nIf you want to run a coupled case and keep the output, you need to use docker volumes, which can be done as follows:\n\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\nsudo docker run -it --name cplrun --mount source=cpl-vol,target=/cplruns cpllibrary/cpl-library\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\n\nThe example codes should then be copied to /cplruns and run in this as above\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"bash\">\nrsync -avP 